question:
Consider $A=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
1 & 1 \\ 
0 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$ and  $B=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
a & b \\ 
c & d \end{array}
\right)$. If $A$ commutes with $B$, (AB = BA) then which of the following statements is correct?

Find ${\left(C^T \cdot B-6 \cdot I^{-1}\right)}^2$, where $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 1 & 1 \\ 
0 & 0 & 3 \end{array}
\right)$, $C=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
3 & 3 & 1 \\ 
1 & -2 & 2 \end{array}
\right)$, and $I$  -- identity matrix.

Let  $A=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
1 & 3 \\ 
2 & -1 \end{array}
\right)$ and $f\left(x\right)=x^3-2x+5I_{2\times2}$. Find $f(A)$.

Find ${\left(C^T \cdot B-6 \cdot I^{-1}\right)}^2$, where $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 1 & 1 \\ 
0 & 0 & 3 \end{array}
\right)$, $C=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
3 & 3 & 1 \\ 
1 & -2 & 2 \end{array}
\right)$, and $I$  -- identity matrix.

Find $M^2+(A^T\cdot B)^{-1}$, where $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 3 & 2 \end{array}
\right)$, $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-2 & 4 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$, and $M=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
7 & 2 & 1 \\
-1 & 3 & 0  \\
2 & 0 & -2 \end{array}
\right)$.

Find the real values of $m$ for which the following set of vectors $V=\left( \begin{array}{r}  
1\\ 
2 \\
m \end{array}
\right)$, $Z=\left( \begin{array}{r}  
1\\ 
-1 \\
m \end{array}
\right)$, and
$W=\left( \begin{array}{r}  
3\\ 
m+2 \\
1 \end{array}
\right)$ is linearly independent.

Let  $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 2 & 0\\ 
1 & 0 & 2\\ 
0 & 1 & 1\end{array}
\right)$ and $g\left(x\right)=x^2-2x-3I_{3\times 3}$. Find $\mathrm{det} \left(g(A) \right)$.

Find $M^2+(A^T\cdot B)^{-1}$, where $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 3 & 2 \end{array}
\right)$, $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-2 & 4 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$, and $M=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
7 & 2 & 1 \\
-1 & 3 & 0  \\
2 & 0 & -2 \end{array}
\right)$.

Suppose that $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
0 & 0 & 1 \\ 
4 & -1 & 2 \\ 
-1 & 0 & -2 \end{array}
\right)$ and $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
4 & 1 & 0 \\ 
-4 & -2 & 4 \\ 
0 & 3 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$.

Find $\mathrm{det} \left(X\right)$ if  $A \cdot X\cdot B -B^2=0$.

Let $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 2 & 0 \\ 
2 & -4 & 0 \end{array}
\right)$. Which of the following statements is correct?

Find $M^2+(A^T\cdot B)^{-1}$, where $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 3 & 2 \end{array}
\right)$, $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-2 & 4 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$, and $M=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
7 & 2 & 1 \\
-1 & 3 & 0  \\
2 & 0 & -2 \end{array}
\right)$.
